-- 
CHILE DAYBOOK: Government to Announce March Unemployment Rate

-- B y   R a n d y   W o o d s
-- 
2011-04-29T03:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-29/chile-daybook-government-to-announce-march-unemployment-rate.html
The Chilean government’s statistics
institute discloses the  unemployment rate  for the three months
through March from its Santiago office at 8 a.m. New York time.  The median estimate of 15 economists surveyed by Bloomberg
was for the jobless rate to grow to 7.5 percent from 7.3 percent
in the three months through February.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*The finance ministry’s budget office to disclose first-quarter
fiscal accounts at 10 a.m. New York time.
*Retailers Cencosud SA and Empresas La Polar SA, Lan Airlines SA
and pulp producer Empresas CMPC SA are scheduled to hold
shareholder meetings in Santiago.  ECONOMY:
*Chile’s industrial production expanded by a record 30.9 percent
in March from the previous year as the South American country’s
pulp and refining industries recovered from the worst earthquake
in decades, the National Statistics Institute said in a report.
*Chilean policy makers discussed a quarter-point rate increase
at their April 12 meeting, before unanimously deciding to raise
rates by a half point for the second straight month, according
to minutes published yesterday.  EQUITIES:
*The Ipsa index rose 0.1 percent to 4,757.99.
*Embotelladora Andina SA fell 0.2 to 2,240 pesos after two days
of gains.  Chile ’s largest Coca-Cola bottler reported a 15
percent drop in first-quarter profit as raw material costs rose.
*Empresa Nacional de Telecomunicaciones SA rose 4.1 percent to a
record 9,096.1 pesos. Chile’s second-largest mobile telephone
operator is scheduled to report first-quarter results May 2.
Some investors are betting results will be “significantly”
higher than a year earlier, Mauricio Seguel, an analyst at Banco
Santander SA, said by telephone.
*Sonda SA increased 2.8 percent to a record 1,298.4 pesos.
Chile’s largest information technology company expects sales of
more than $1 billion this year, Diario Financiero reported,
citing Chief Executive Officer Raul Vejar.  MARKETS:
*Chile’s peso reached a three-year high, climbing 0.3 percent to
460.82 per  U.S. dollar .
*Inflation expectations fell for a second day. The two-year
breakeven inflation rate slid eight basis points as of 12:42
p.m. New York time to 3.67 percent, the lowest since Jan. 6
according to Bloomberg data. The one-year breakeven rate fell
six basis points to 3.88 percent, the lowest since Jan. 12.
*Foreign investors in the forwards market had a $1.5 billion bet
that the peso would fall against the dollar as of April 26,
according to central bank data.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
